msContents.summary: Collection of Aristotelian works and other philosophical works, including works on logic; short tracts (some incomplete) on Aristotle's Categories, De interpretatione, and Posterior analytics; and several works on Aristotle's Physics (including commentaries by Antonius Carpentier on both the Physics and the introduction to the Physics by Jacques Lefèvre d'Etaples published in 1492), this last group (f. 148v-206r) being more decorated than the rest of the manuscript. The beginning of the Reportata in Logicam Aristotelis has a marginal commentary (f. 22r-29v); in the rest of the manuscript, headings and notes are written in the margins.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 27-40 long lines; frame-ruled in faint red ink with double vertical bounding lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in batârde script, probably in the hand of Theodoricus Ungelter (f. 153r).

decoDesc.decoNote: 5 philosophical diagrams in color washes (f. 148v, 153v, 157v, 159v, 162v-163r); 16 philosophical and geometrical tables and diagrams in brown and sometimes red ink (f. 63v, 66r, 75r, 75v, 78r, 78v, 89v, 90r, 116v, 141v, 202v, 203v-204r, 205r-206r); 9 decorated initials, 6 to 10 lines in height, in color washes (f. 149r, 154v, 158v, 163v, 170r, 172r, 173v, 177r (with faces), 178v); geometric lower borders or line-fillers of diamonds in color washes (f. 158r, 159r, 175v, 203r); some caption titles and colophons in alternating letters, words, or lines of red, yellow and blue (for example, f. 7v, 14r, 154r, 176r); rubrics, marginal notes and headings, and underlining in red throughout; sketch in ink of man (inside lower cover). Some spaces for initials and possibly diagrams left blank.

binding.p: Contemporary blind-stamped calf, rebacked, with title label (Questiones logicales CXCIX) on upper cover.

origin.p: Written in Bavaria, ca. 1510 (on the basis of the watermark).

history.provenance: Owned and probably written by Theodoricus Ungelter (f. 153r).

Gift of Johannes Wesbach of Ulm to Carthusian monastery at Buxheim (inscriptions inside upper cover; Wesbach served as a judge in Ulm from 1499 to 1507); then in the library at Buxheim (Cartusianorum Aulae B. V. Mariae in Buxheim, f. 1r; number CXCIX added to label on upper cover).
Appears in a catalog of J. Halle Antiquariat (Munich).
Sold by Les Enluminures (Paris and Chicago) to Lawrence J. Schoenberg, 1997.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2011.
